column1: # Periodic table used in HORTON
# To make the numbers verifiable, the provenance of each data column is given below.
# Only numbers literally mentioned in these papers are included.
# When some data is not provided in the reference for a given element, the cell is left empty.
# A: atomic number
# B: atomic symbol
# C: name
# D: group
# E: period
# F: covalent radius (derived from crystallographic data)
#     B. Cordero, V. Gomez, A. E. Platero-Prats, M. Reves, J. Echeverria, E. Cremades, F. Barragan, and S. Alvarez, Dalton Trans. pp. 2832--2838 (2008)
#     http://dx.doi.org/10.1039/b801115j
#     For carbon the number is a weighted average over the data for different hybridizations.
#     For Mn, Fe, and Co, the number is a weighted average over the data for different spins (high spin and low spin)
# G: Bragg radius (covalent, metallic and ionic bonds, derived from crystallographic data)
#     W. L. Bragg, Phil. Mag. 40, 169 (1920)
# H: Slater radius (covalent, metallic and ionic bonds, derived from crystallographic data)
#     J. C. Slater, J. Chem. Phys. 41, 3199 (1964)
# I: van der Waals radius according to Bondi
#     A. Bondi, J. Phys. Chem. 68, 441 (1964)
# J: van der Waals radii by Truhlar (corrections and additions to Bondi)
#     M. Mantina  A. C. Chamberlin  R. Valero  C. J. Cramer  D. G. Truhlar  J. Phys. Chem. A 113  5806 (2009)
# K: van der Waals radius according to Rowland and Taylor
#     R. S. Rowland and R. Taylor, J. Phys. Chem. 100, 7384 (1996)
# L: van der Waals radii by Batsanov
#     S. S. Batsanov Inorganic Materials 37 871 (2001)
# M: van der Waals radii from the DREIDING FF (R_0 parameter, unit 2angstrom is used so that numbers are divided by 2 upon reading)
#     Stephen L. Mayo, Barry D. Olafson, and William A. Goddard III J. Phys. Chem. 94 8897 (1990)
# N: van der Waals radii from UFF (x_I parameter, unit 2angstrom is used so that numbers are divided by 2 upon reading)
#     A. K. Rappi, C. J. Casewit, K. S. Colwell, W. A. Goddard III, and W. M. Skid J. Am. Chem. Soc. 114 10024 (1992)
# O: van der Waals radii from MM3
#     N. L. Allinger, X. Zhou, and J. Bergsma, Journal of Molecular Structure: THEOCHEM 312, 69 (1994)
# P: Waber-Cromer radius
#     J. T. Waber and D. T. Cromer, J. Chem. Phys. 42, 4116 (1965)
#     For each element, the largest radius of the outer orbitals is taken.
# Q: Clementi-Raimondi radius
#     E. Clementi, D. L. Raimondi, W. P. Reinhardt, J. Chem. Phys. 47, 1300 (1967)
# R: Pauling electronegativity
#     A. L. Allred, J. Inorg. Nuc. Chem. 17, 215 (1961)
# S: Isolated atom dipole polarizability
#     CRC Handbook of Chemistry and Physics (CRC, Boca Raton, FL, 2003).
#     If multiple values were present in the CRC book, the value used in Erin's postg code is taken
# T: Isolated atom dipole polarizability
#     X. Chu & A. Dalgarno, J. Chem. Phys., 121(9), 4083–4088 (2004)
#     Theoretical value for hydrogen from this paper:
#     A.D. Buckingham, K.L. Clarke, Chem. Phys. Lett. 57(3), 321--325 (1978)
# U: Isolated atom C6 dispersion coefficients
#     X. Chu & A. Dalgarno, J. Chem. Phys., 121(9), 4083–4088 (2004)
#     Theoretical value for hydrogen from this paper:
#     K. T. Tang, J. M. Norbeck and P. R. Certain, J. Chem. Phys. 64, 3063 (1976)
# V: IUPAC atomic mass (or weight for the chemists)
#    T.B. Coplen, W.A. Brand, J. Meija, M. Gröning, N.E. Holden, M. Berglund, P. De Bièvre, R.D. Loss, T. Prohaska, and T. Walczyk. ciaaw.org (2013)
#    http://www.ciaaw.org/pubs/TSAW2013_xls.xls
#    When ranges are provided, the middle of the range is used
number
int
